08-11-2021Court trialAnderson, John P.Nordin, Denise D
Additional text:
Attorney Linda Irene Coleman in court for Plaintiff Ed Westlund. Plaintiff Ed Westlund in court. Defendant Lynsey Duke in court. Attorney Linda Coleman: No agreement. Lynsey Duke: Contesting eviction. Break taken at 9:03 AM for parties to discuss.

Back on record at 9:08 AM.  Lynsey Duke sworn in.  Adversely called by Attorney Linda Coleman:  Residence she lives in owned by Ed Westlund.  She not on deed.  Utilities, 1/2 taxes, 1/2 insurance - not in writing.  She offered to pay utilities, etc.  He willing to help while she got on feet.  He purchased home from her father so she could stay there.  Water bill - in her name, past due. Property taxes - she not paid, she never saw a bill.  Insurance policy - she unable to renew, her name not on deed.
Exhibit #1 - Letter from Atty. Max Lindsey dated 4/15/21.  Required her to vacate within 28 days.  She still living in house.  No written lease, just verbal.

Ed Westlund sworn in.  Direct by Attorney Linda Coleman:  He owns property at 411 W. Pine St., Washburn.  Purchased house in October 2020 for $30,000.  No one else on deed.  He agreed Lynsey Duke could stay on property -  she to pay utilities, 1/2 insurance, 1/2 taxes.  Tax bill in Jan. 2021 - she couldn't pay.  Insurance policy - expired, late notice.  He got other insurance.    Exhibit #2 - Water bill in Defendant's name - past due $580.68 as of 8/10/21.  Wants Defendant to be responsible for bill.  Defendant did not vacate home after letter from Attorney Lindsey.  Wants eviction order.  Planning to sell house, has potential buyer.  No agreement with Defendant to stay in house.
Cross by Lynsey Duke:  Spoke with her over the weekend, doesn't remember what all about.
Redirect by Attorney Linda Coleman:  No promises to Defendant to stay in home, no lease agreement.  Wants eviction.  House paid outright when bought, no mortgage.
Exhibits #1 and #2 - received.    No testimony by Defendant.

Attorney Linda Coleman final argument:  Plaintiff's generosity to let Defendant stay in home is exhausted.  She has no legal right to stay, he wants to sell.  Entitled to Judgment of eviction and for payment of water bill in amount of $580.68.  Not asking for unpaid taxes and insurance.
Lynsey Duke final argument:  Plaintiff told her she could stay, never told her she had to leave. Agreement was that she could live there.

Judge: No legal basis for Defendant to stay, 28 day notice given. Plaintiff owns property, Defendant is renter. Satisfied notice to terminate tenancy was given with equitable grounds to do so. Defendant admits her responsibility to pay. No agreement was made in writing. Plaintiff is entitled to eviction and judgment for $580.68. If Plaintiff wants Writ, will sign. Suggests Defendant speak with DHS for housing assistance.07-19-2021Contested07-19-2021Return dateAnderson, John P.Nordin, Denise D
